{{Infobox language |name=Biksi-Yetfa |nativename=Biksi |states=[[Indonesia]], [[Papua New Guinea]] |region=[[West Papua (region)|West Papua]] |ethnicity=[[Yetfa people|Yetfa]], [[Biksi people|Biksi]] |speakers=1,000 |date=1996 |ref=e18 |familycolor=Papuan |fam1=[[Pauwasi languages|Pauwasi]] |fam2=Southern |script= [[Latin script]] |iso3=yet |glotto=yetf1238 |glottorefname=Yetfa |dia1=Yetfa |dia2=Biksi }}
'''Yetfa''' and '''Biksi''' (Biaksi) are dialects of a language spoken in [[West Papua (region)|West Papua]], [[Indonesia]], and across the border in [[Papua New Guinea]]. It's a trade language in West Papua up to the PNG border.
The language is not close to others. Ross (2005), following Laycock & Z’Graggen (1975), places Biksi in its own branch of the [[Sepik languages|Sepik]] family, but there is little data to base a classification on. The similarities noted by Laycock are sporadic and may simply be loans; Ross based his classification on pronouns, but they are dissimilar enough for the connection to be uncertain. Usher found it to be a Southern Pauwasi language. According to Hammarström (2008), it's being passed on to children and is not in immediate danger.
